# Contributing to Ontask

First off, thank you for considering contributing to Ontask! ðŸŽ‰

The following is a guide to help you get started with contributing. Please take a moment to review these guidelines before submitting your contributions.

## How to Contribute

### 1. Fork the repository

Start by forking the repository to your own GitHub account. You can do this by clicking the "Fork" button in the upper-right corner of the projectâ€™s GitHub page.

### 2. Clone your fork

Clone the forked repository to your local machine using:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/ontask.git
```

### 3. Create a new branch

Create a new branch for your changes. Make sure to name it descriptively:

```bash
git checkout -b your-branch-name
```

### 4. Make your changes

Make your changes locally. Please ensure that your code adheres to the projectâ€™s coding style, and try to avoid introducing breaking changes unless absolutely necessary.

### 5. Commit your changes

After making your changes, commit them with a clear message describing what was done:

```bash
git commit -m "Describe your changes here"
```

### 6. Push your changes

Push your changes to your forked repository:

```bash
git push origin your-branch-name
```

### 7. Create a pull request

Go to your fork on GitHub and open a pull request to the main repository. Include a clear description of the changes you made and why you made them.

## Code Style

- Please follow consistent code formatting. Refer to existing code for conventions.
- Use meaningful names for variables, functions, and classes.
- Write clear and concise commit messages.

## Reporting Issues

If you find any bugs or have feature requests, please open an issue on the GitHub repository. Be sure to include as much detail as possible, such as:

- Steps to reproduce the bug
- Expected vs. actual behavior
- Any relevant logs or error messages

## Code of Conduct

Please be respectful and considerate when interacting with others. Follow the project's [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).

## Questions?

Feel free to open an issue or reach out to me directly at [aslanreza77@gmail.com].
